<paragraph blockId="21.[151,1437,1364,2038]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,418,1796,1822]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Biology and notes.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thompson &amp; Marnef" authorityYear="1977" box="[425,644,1796,1822]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Austroascia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="segersi">
<emphasis box="[425,644,1796,1822]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Austroascia segersi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is associated with native trees such as 
<taxonomicName authority="J. R. Forst. &amp; G. Forst." authorityName="J. R. Forst. &amp; G. Forst." class="Magnoliopsida" family="Winteraceae" genus="Drimys" kingdom="Plantae" order="Canellales" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="winteri">
<emphasis box="[1081,1250,1797,1822]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Drimys winteri</emphasis>
J.R. Forst. &amp; G. Forst.
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Cav." authorityName="Cav." box="[231,523,1832,1858]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cunoniaceae" genus="Eucryphia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Oxalidales" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="cordifolia">
<emphasis box="[231,464,1832,1858]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Eucryphia cordifolia</emphasis>
Cav.
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="(Hook. &amp; Arn.) O. Berg" authorityName="O. Berg" baseAuthorityName="Hook. &amp; Arn." box="[579,1108,1832,1859]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Myrtaceae" genus="Myrceugenia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Myrtales" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="planipes">
<emphasis box="[579,828,1832,1858]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Myrceugenia planipes</emphasis>
(Hook. &amp; Arn.) O. Berg
</taxonomicName>
(Thomspon &amp; Marnef 1977; C. Smith-Ramírez pers. obs.). Throughout its distribution range, many ecosystems have been negatively affected by plantation forestry, croplands and urbanization (
<bibRefCitation author="Alaniz, A. J. &amp; Galleguillos, M. &amp; Perez-Quezada, J. F." box="[693,903,1904,1930]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" pagination="378 - 385" refId="ref123551" refString="Alaniz, A. J., Galleguillos, M. &amp; Perez-Quezada, J. F. (2016) Assessment of quality of input data used to classify ecosystems according to the IUCN Red List methodology: The case of the central Chile hotspot. Biological Conservation, 204, 378 - 385. https: // doi. org / 10.1016 / j. biocon. 2016.10.038" type="journal article" year="2016">
Alaniz 
<emphasis box="[778,835,1904,1930]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">et al.</emphasis>
2016
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Miranda, A. &amp; Altamirano, A. &amp; Cayuela, L. &amp; Lara, A. &amp; Gonzalez, M." box="[915,1145,1904,1930]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" pagination="285 - 297" refId="ref134460" refString="Miranda, A., Altamirano, A., Cayuela, L., Lara, A. &amp; Gonzalez, M. (2017) Native forest loss in the Chilean biodiversity hotspot: revealing the evidence. Regional Environmental Change, 17, 285 - 297. https: // doi. org / 10.1007 / s 10113 - 016 - 1010 - 7" type="journal article" year="2017">
<collectingRegion box="[915,1010,1904,1930]" country="Venezuela" name="Miranda" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Miranda</collectingRegion>
<emphasis box="[1018,1076,1904,1930]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">et al.</emphasis>
2017
</bibRefCitation>
). Both males and females are dichoptic (
<figureCitation box="[313,442,1940,1967]" captionStart="FIGURES 16–19" captionStartId="22.[151,264,1117,1141]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,236,1093]" captionTargetId="figure-46@22.[151,1436,236,1093]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="FIGURES 16–19. Austroascia segersii Thompson &amp; Marnef, 1977: (16) male, dorsal view; (17) male, lateral view; (18) male, frontal, view; (19) female, dorsal view. Scale bars = 1 mm (all photos by Vicente Valdés)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4693479" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4693479/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Figs 16–19</figureCitation>
) and sexual dimorphism is generated by the maculae pattern and color of the abdomen. Males present enlarged and yellowish maculae located near the abdominal margin. Females do not present maculae and the abdominal color is reddish.
</paragraph>
